---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro'
import MapLink from '../../components/MapLink.astro'
---

<Base
  title="Bermuda Events Calendar"
  description="A resident's guide to Bermuda's annual events — Cup Match, Bermuda Day, Restaurant Week, the Christmas Boat Parade, and what's worth knowing month by month."
>
  <section class="hero" style="padding-block: var(--space-16);">
    <div class="hero__inner">
      <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb">
        <ol class="breadcrumb" style="justify-content: center; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">
          <li><a href="/Pilot.BM/" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">Home</a></li>
          <li class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</li>
          <li><a href="/Pilot.BM/live" style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.6);">Living</a></li>
          <li class="breadcrumb__sep" aria-hidden="true">›</li>
          <li style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.9);">Events Calendar</li>
        </ol>
      </nav>
      <h1 class="hero-title">Bermuda Events Calendar</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">
        What's happening, when, and why it matters.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="container" style="padding-block: var(--space-12);">

    <!-- Why this page exists -->
    <section style="max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto var(--space-12);">
      <h2 style="font-size: var(--text-2xl); margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">Why this page exists</h2>
      <p style="color: var(--color-ink); margin-bottom: var(--space-4); line-height: 1.75;">
        For years, nothingtodoinbermuda.com was the default community events calendar — informal,
        comprehensive, and genuinely useful. When it was absorbed into the Bermuda Tourism Authority
        portal, something was lost. The BTA does solid work covering tourist-facing events, but
        community-level notices, local sports fixtures, and the texture of ordinary island life
        don't have a clean home anywhere online.
      </p>
      <p style="color: var(--color-ink); margin-bottom: var(--space-4); line-height: 1.75;">
        This page fills part of that gap. It is not a live events feed. What it is: a reliable
        orientation to the annual calendar, the events worth planning around, and the context a
        newcomer needs to avoid missing something genuinely memorable.
      </p>
      <p style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: var(--text-sm);">
        Specific dates shift year to year. Always verify with the BTA events calendar or Bernews
        before making travel plans or booking time off work.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- Monthly overview -->
    <section style="margin-bottom: var(--space-12);">
      <h2 style="font-size: var(--text-2xl); margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">The year at a glance</h2>
      <div style="overflow-x: auto;">
        <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: var(--text-sm);">
          <thead>
            <tr style="background-color: var(--color-ocean); color: white; text-align: left;">
              <th style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); width: 120px; white-space: nowrap;">Month</th>
              <th style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4);">Key events and what to know</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);">
              <td style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); font-weight: 600; vertical-align: top;">January</td>
              <td style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); color: var(--color-ink);">
                New Year recovery. Local sports leagues (football, cricket) resume. Quiet on the
                social calendar — a good month to explore uncrowded beaches and hiking trails.
                Some restaurants closed for annual breaks through mid-January.
                Hotel rates at their annual low.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border); background-color: var(--color-sand);">
              <td style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); font-weight: 600; vertical-align: top;">February – March</td>
              <td style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); color: var(--color-ink);">
                Quiet shoulder season. Genuinely good for exploring — trails aren't crowded,
                restaurants are reachable without reservations, and locals are visible.
                Good month for diving and snorkelling before summer crowds arrive.
                Local football season mid-run. February brings prix-fixe Valentine's specials
                at many Hamilton restaurants.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);">
              <td style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); font-weight: 600; vertical-align: top;">April</td>
              <td style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); color: var(--color-ink);">
                <strong>Agricultural Exhibition (Show Week):</strong> four days at the Botanical Gardens <MapLink query="Botanical Gardens, Bermuda" /> —
                animals, produce, food stalls, carnival rides. One of the most genuinely local
                events on the calendar; the island stops for it.
                <strong>Peppercorn Ceremony</strong> in St. George's — the Freemasons pay one peppercorn
                rent to the government for use of the State House <MapLink query="State House, St. George's, Bermuda" />. Full ceremonial regalia, free
                to watch, genuinely worth seeing once.
                Fitted dinghy racing season begins.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border); background-color: var(--color-sand);">
              <td style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); font-weight: 600; vertical-align: top;">May</td>
              <td style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); color: var(--color-ink);">
                <strong>Bermuda Day (24 May) — public holiday.</strong> Kite flying from first light on
                South Shore beaches. The fitted dinghy race through the Great Sound. The Heritage
                Parade through Hamilton with Gombey dancers, floats, and community groups.
                The half-marathon from Hamilton to the South Shore. The first day Bermudians
                traditionally swim in the ocean. One of the best days on the island if you are
                here for it — see below.
                Fitted dinghy racing in full swing through summer.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);">
              <td style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); font-weight: 600; vertical-align: top;">June</td>
              <td style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); color: var(--color-ink);">
                <strong>Bermuda Heroes Weekend</strong> — the island's Carnival, spanning multiple events
                over the long weekend: J'ouvert from early morning, the Parade of Bands through
                Hamilton. Loud, colourful, and a genuine community event, not a tourist production.
                Hamilton road closures in effect on parade day.
                Fitted dinghy races continue.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border); background-color: var(--color-sand);">
              <td style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); font-weight: 600; vertical-align: top;">July – August</td>
              <td style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); color: var(--color-ink);">
                <strong>Cup Match</strong> (late July or early August bank holiday, Thursday–Friday):
                the annual cricket match between Somerset Cricket Club and St. George's Cricket Club.
                The social event of the year — camping, boats moored alongside the ground, Crown
                &amp; Anchor gambling (legal only this weekend), food vendors, sound systems.
                See the full breakdown below.
                <strong>Bermuda Shark Tournament.</strong> Peak season: beaches at their best, regattas.
                Book accommodation months ahead.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);">
              <td style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); font-weight: 600; vertical-align: top;">September</td>
              <td style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); color: var(--color-ink);">
                <strong>Bermuda International Film Festival</strong> — screenings across multiple venues;
                strong independent and short film programme with local and international entries.
                Early shoulder season: sea still warm, crowds thinning, prices beginning to ease.
                Hurricane season awareness, though direct hits are uncommon.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border); background-color: var(--color-sand);">
              <td style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); font-weight: 600; vertical-align: top;">October</td>
              <td style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); color: var(--color-ink);">
                <strong>Marine Science Day</strong> at BIOS (Bermuda Institute of Ocean Sciences) <MapLink query="Bermuda Institute of Ocean Sciences, Bermuda" /> —
                open labs, marine ecology demonstrations, research vessel tours, good for families.
                Shoulder season proper: October is Bermuda's most underrated month. Comfortable
                temperatures, empty trails, excellent diving visibility, uncrowded beaches.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);">
              <td style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); font-weight: 600; vertical-align: top;">November</td>
              <td style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); color: var(--color-ink);">
                <strong>Bermuda Restaurant Week</strong> — prix-fixe menus at 50+ restaurants across the
                island. Two or three courses at a fixed price (typically $45–$55) that represents
                real value against normal Bermuda dining costs. The best time of year to eat out
                if you live here. See the full breakdown below, including how to use Table.bm.
                <strong>PWC Marathon</strong> — the annual road race through the parishes, one of the
                world's more scenic marathon routes.
              </td>
            </tr>
            <tr style="border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border); background-color: var(--color-sand);">
              <td style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); font-weight: 600; vertical-align: top;">December</td>
              <td style="padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); color: var(--color-ink);">
                <strong>Christmas Boat Parade</strong> in Hamilton Harbour <MapLink query="Hamilton Harbour, Bermuda" /> — decorated boats parade through
                the harbour on a Friday evening in mid-December. Free to watch from the waterfront.
                Genuinely spectacular; do not miss this if you are new to the island.
                Carolling events in Hamilton.
                <strong>New Year's Eve</strong> on Front Street — outdoor celebrations and fireworks
                over the harbour.
              </td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Featured events deep dives -->
    <section style="margin-bottom: var(--space-12);">
      <h2 style="font-size: var(--text-2xl); margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">Three events worth understanding properly</h2>

      <!-- Cup Match -->
      <div style="background-color: var(--color-sand); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: var(--space-8); margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-xs); font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--color-ocean); margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Late July or Early August — Public Holiday (Thu–Fri)</p>
        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-2xl); margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">Cup Match</h3>
        <p style="color: var(--color-ink); margin-bottom: var(--space-4); line-height: 1.75;">
          If you only experience one Bermudian institution, make it this one. Cup Match is a
          two-day cricket match between the East End (St. George's Cricket Club <MapLink query="St. George's Cricket Club, Bermuda" />) and the West End
          (Somerset Cricket Club <MapLink query="Somerset Cricket Club, Bermuda" />). It has been played since 1902. The date is a public holiday —
          Emancipation Day and Mary Prince Day are observed on the Thursday and Friday, giving
          everyone a long weekend built around the match. The history matters: the match was
          organised to mark the abolition of slavery in Bermuda, and that weight is present.
        </p>
        <p style="color: var(--color-ink); margin-bottom: var(--space-4); line-height: 1.75;">
          The cricket itself is serious — both clubs field strong players and the rivalry is real.
          But the match is also the frame for a social event unlike anything else on the island.
          At the host ground (it alternates yearly between Somerset and St. George's), the
          perimeter fills with vendor tents, barbecue stalls, and sound systems. Families set up
          camps for both days. Boats anchor in the cove at Somerset's ground. Crown and Anchor —
          a dice game legal in Bermuda only during Cup Match weekend — draws crowds who have
          never watched a cricket ball in their lives.
        </p>
        <p style="color: var(--color-ink); margin-bottom: var(--space-4); line-height: 1.75;">
          For newcomers: pick a side (Somerset or St. George's — locals will ask), bring cash,
          dress for sun and an impromptu rain shower, and plan to stay longer than you intended.
          Tickets are purchased at the gate. The ferry from Hamilton to Somerset is the better
          option if the match is at the western ground — parking is limited and traffic is
          substantial.
        </p>
        <p style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: var(--text-sm);">
          Exact dates announced annually. Check Bernews or the Bermuda Cricket Board closer to the season.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Bermuda Day -->
      <div style="background-color: var(--color-sand); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: var(--space-8); margin-bottom: var(--space-8);">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-xs); font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--color-ocean); margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">24 May — Public Holiday</p>
        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-2xl); margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">Bermuda Day</h3>
        <p style="color: var(--color-ink); margin-bottom: var(--space-4); line-height: 1.75;">
          Bermuda Day is the cultural centrepiece of the spring calendar. It begins before sunrise
          on South Shore beaches, where families gather to fly kites — box kites, fighter kites,
          homemade kites, elaborate constructions built specifically for the day. Kite flying on
          Bermuda Day is a tradition with no particular origin story; it is simply what Bermudians
          do here, and has been for as long as anyone can track.
        </p>
        <p style="color: var(--color-ink); margin-bottom: var(--space-4); line-height: 1.75;">
          The fitted dinghy race runs from Ely's Harbour <MapLink query="Ely's Harbour, Bermuda" /> through the Great Sound to Hamilton
          Harbour. These are the traditional Bermudian racing dinghies — narrow, inherently
          unstable craft crewed by large teams who hang off the sides as counterbalance.
          They are not like any other racing class. Watching them pass is worth positioning for.
        </p>
        <p style="color: var(--color-ink); margin-bottom: var(--space-4); line-height: 1.75;">
          The Heritage Parade moves through Hamilton in the afternoon: Gombey dancers, floats,
          community groups, marching bands, local schools. The Gombeys — masked dancers in
          elaborate feathered and mirrored costumes, moving to a driving percussion beat — are
          one of Bermuda's most distinctive cultural expressions, drawing from West African,
          Native American, and Caribbean influences developed on the island over centuries.
          Seek them out on the parade route; they are worth seeing up close.
        </p>
        <p style="color: var(--color-ink); margin-bottom: var(--space-4); line-height: 1.75;">
          By tradition, 24 May is also the first day Bermudians swim in the ocean for the year.
          The water is warm enough by May, but the ritual matters independent of the temperature.
          The Half Marathon Derby (Somerset to Hamilton) starts early morning.
        </p>
        <p style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: var(--text-sm);">
          Bermuda Day falls on 24 May annually. If 24 May falls on a weekend, the public holiday
          shifts to the adjacent Friday or Monday — verify the official holiday dates each year.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Restaurant Week -->
      <div style="background-color: var(--color-sand); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: var(--space-8);">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-xs); font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: 0.08em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--color-ocean); margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">November — typically 10–14 days</p>
        <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-2xl); margin-bottom: var(--space-4);">Bermuda Restaurant Week</h3>
        <p style="color: var(--color-ink); margin-bottom: var(--space-4); line-height: 1.75;">
          Bermuda dining is excellent and expensive. Restaurant Week in November is the one period
          per year when the economics shift meaningfully in your favour. More than 50 restaurants
          across the island offer prix-fixe menus — typically two or three courses at a fixed
          price in the $45–$55 range. That represents real value against the same restaurants'
          normal a la carte pricing, where a comparable dinner for two routinely runs $120–$150
          before tip.
        </p>
        <p style="color: var(--color-ink); margin-bottom: var(--space-4); line-height: 1.75;">
          The programme runs for roughly two weeks (the "week" in the name is a branding
          convention). Participating restaurants range from hotel dining rooms to neighbourhood
          spots that rarely run promotions. It's a genuine opportunity to try restaurants you
          might not otherwise book, or to return to favourites at a fraction of the usual cost.
        </p>
        <p style="color: var(--color-ink); margin-bottom: var(--space-4); line-height: 1.75;">
          <strong>How to use it:</strong> <a href="https://www.table.bm" rel="noopener" target="_blank" style="color: var(--color-ocean);">Table.bm</a>
          lists participating restaurants and allows direct reservations. Book early — popular
          restaurants fill within the first few days of bookings opening. Check the Table.bm
          deals section year-round for regular dining specials; it remains the best tool for
          Bermuda dining regardless of the season.
        </p>
        <p style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: var(--text-sm);">
          Dates vary annually. The BTA and Table.bm typically announce the programme in October.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- How to stay informed -->
    <section style="background-color: var(--color-sand); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); padding: var(--space-8); margin-bottom: var(--space-12);">
      <h2 style="font-size: var(--text-2xl); margin-bottom: var(--space-6);">How to stay informed</h2>
      <div class="card-grid card-grid-3">
        <div>
          <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-lg); margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">BTA Events Calendar</h3>
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-ink); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
            The Bermuda Tourism Authority maintains the most complete calendar of official events.
            Best for confirmed dates of major recurring events and anything involving ticketed venues.
          </p>
          <a href="https://www.gotobermuda.com/events" rel="noopener" target="_blank"
             style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-ocean); font-weight: 600;">
            gotobermuda.com/events →
          </a>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-lg); margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Bernews</h3>
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-ink); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
            The closest thing Bermuda has to a community bulletin board. Covers everything from
            road closures to event announcements to local sports results. Check it weekly.
          </p>
          <a href="https://bernews.com" rel="noopener" target="_blank"
             style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-ocean); font-weight: 600;">
            bernews.com →
          </a>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 style="font-size: var(--text-lg); margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">Table.bm for Dining</h3>
          <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-ink); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
            Restaurant reservations, dining events, and the best real-time view of Restaurant
            Week availability. Use it year-round, not just in November.
          </p>
          <a href="https://www.table.bm" rel="noopener" target="_blank"
             style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-ocean); font-weight: 600;">
            table.bm →
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p style="margin-top: var(--space-6); font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--color-muted);">
        For venue information — addresses, hours, contact details — the
        <a href="/Pilot.BM/directory" style="color: var(--color-ocean);">Pilot.BM directory</a>
        covers restaurants, venues, and local businesses across all parishes.
        Specific dates change annually; always verify before making firm plans.
      </p>
    </section>

  </div>
</Base>
